title: Blencathra
description: Blencathra, also known as Saddleback, is one of the most northerly hills in the English Lake District. It has six separate fell tops, of which the highest is the Hallsfell Top at 2,848 feet (868 metres). For many years, Ordnance Survey listed Blencathra under the alternative name of Saddleback, which was coined in reference to the shape of the mountain when seen from the east. The guidebook author Alfred Wainwright popularised the use of the older Cumbric name, which is now used almost exclusively. Ordnance Survey currently marks the summit as ‘Saddleback or Blencathra’. It is likely that the name Blencathra is derived from the Cumbric elements *blain ‘top, summit’ and cadeir ‘seat, chair’, meaning ‘the summit of the seat-like mountain’. Andrew Breeze has proposed an alternative interpretation of the second element of the name, arguing that it represents a Cumbric cognate of Middle Welsh carthwr ‘working horse’. Richard Coates has suggested that the second element may be the Middle Irish personal name Carthach, but writes that ‘the implications of that with a Brittonic generic need exploring’ The Northern Fells make up a roughly circular upland area about 10 miles (16 km) wide. At the centre is the marshy depression of Skiddaw Forest — a treeless plateau at an altitude of 1,300 ft (396 m.) — and flowing outward from here are the rivers which divide the area into three sectors. The southeastern sector, between the Glenderaterra Beck and the River Caldew, contains Blencathra and its satellites. Blencathra is more of a small range than a single fell, a series of tops standing out on a curving ridge 3 miles (5 kilometres) long. It has smooth, easy slopes to the north and west, whilst displaying a complex system of rocky spurs and scree slopes to the south and east. When viewed from the southeast, particularly on the main Keswick to Penrith road, Blencathra appears almost symmetrical. To left and right, the ends of the fell rise from the surrounding lowlands in smooth and sweeping curves, clad in rough grass. Each rises gracefully to a ridge-top summit, Blease Fell on the west and Scales Fell to the east. Between these ‘book-ends’ are a further three tops, Gategill Fell, Hallsfell and Doddick Fell, giving a scalloped profile to the ridge. From each of the three central tops, a spur runs out at right angles to the main ridge, beginning as a narrow, rocky arête and then widening into a broad buttress which falls 2,000 ft (610 m) to the base of the fell. Separating the five tops are four streams which run down the south-east face between the spurs. From the west these are Blease Gill, Gate Gill, Doddick Gill and Scaley Beck. In addition to the spurs on the southeast face, Hallsfell also throws out a high ridge to the north. This is the saddle that gives Blencathra its alternative name, rising beyond the dip to the sixth top, Atkinson Pike. This is the focal point for connecting ridges to Bannerdale Crags and Mungrisdale Common to the north. The ‘saddle’ is bounded by crags to the east, Tarn Crag and Foule Crag being the principal faces. In common with much of the Northern Fells, the Kirk Stile Formation of the Skiddaw Group predominates. This is composed of laminated mudstone and siltstone with greywacke sandstone and is of Ordovician age. There has been considerable mining activity beneath the slopes of Blencathra. Threlkeld mine lies at the base of Hallsfell. From 1879 to 1928, it was a profitable venture for the raising of lead and zinc ores and is believed to hold further reserves should the economic situation improve. A small trial working can be seen beside Blease Gill near the 2,000 ft (610 m) contour. This is believed to have been driven for lead. Saddleback Old Mine had workings near Scales Tarn and at Mousthwaite Comb. The mine was driven for lead but in the 1890s raised mostly limonite. This was marketed unsuccessfully as a pigment and the mine closed in 1894. In the Glenderaterra valley to the west of Blease Fell were Brundholme and Blencathra mines. Lead, copper and baryte were raised between the middle of the 19th century and the final closure in 1920.

The Grand Finale
description: The last rich beams of sunlight illuminate the jagged granitic ridges of Apache (l,13,441 ft / 4097 m) and Navajo (r, 13,409 ft / 4087 m) peaks as the sun sinks towards the western horizon. During the sunset transition clouds periodically obscured the sunlight, but fortunately there were some breaks in the clouds that allowed the final warm sunlight to glow on the peaks. This view was from my campsite near Coyote Park in the Indian Peaks wilderness on the western side of the Continental Divide. A 12,000’/ 3600 m pass separated me from the heavily populated eastern slope of the Front Range- I saw no other people this entire day. A couple of hours after taking this photo several severe thunderstorms formed just over the ridges to the right (Arapaho Peaks), generating frequent flashes of lightning reminiscent of strobe lights at a disco bar. I awoke to the light show, though regretfully I didn’t head out of the tent to take photos.

title: Summer's Last Fling
description: Dark clouds roil over the Continental Divide and spit rain down onto summer's last hurrah of alpine wildflowers, Indian Peaks Wilderness, Colorado. The very uppermost reach of Niwot Ridge is visible on the left, with Navajo Peak (13,376 ft; 4,077 m) at its apex. To the right are Apache Peak (13,435 ft; 4,095 m) and Shoshoni Peak (12,936 ft; 3,943 m). Fortunately, this time the family and I remembered to bring warm uppers and rain gear, so everyone was comfortable as the wet foliage and flowers glowed in the overcast atmosphere. We had just finished lunch as well, which was a blessing. For the afternoon repast, I brought several packs of ramen, some delicious freeze-dried corn, as well as freeze-dried mushrooms and chicken. This was cooked over an alcohol stove I made with my oldest son out of two aluminum cans, some fiberglass insulation, a patch of Bondo cloth, and some JB Weld. We fabricated the pot stand from four equal-length pieces of 14 gauge stainless steel wire, each twisted around a nail then bent with a custom jig and cut to length. The four pieces all hook together in a circle to support the weight of the pot. It was a fun project and an even better field test! Then there was chocolate for dessert... Happy Mother's Day to those wonderful women out there who drive the world forward with all of their energy and wisdom!
